/**
28 
 * <p>Operations on arrays, primitive arrays (like <code>int[]</code>) and
29 
 * primitive wrapper arrays (like <code>Integer[]</code>).</p>
30 
 *
31 
 * <p>This class tries to handle <code>null</code> input gracefully.
32 
 * An exception will not be thrown for a <code>null</code>
33 
 * array input. However, an Object array that contains a <code>null</code>
34 
 * element may throw an exception. Each method documents its behaviour.</p>
35 
 *
36 
 * <p>#ThreadSafe#</p>
37 
 * @author Apache Software Foundation
38 
 * @author Moritz Petersen
39 
 * @author <a href="mailto:fredrik@westermarck.com">Fredrik Westermarck</a>
40 
 * @author Nikolay Metchev
41 
 * @author Matthew Hawthorne
42 
 * @author Tim O'Brien
43 
 * @author Pete Gieser
44 
 * @author Gary Gregory
45 
 * @author <a href="mailto:equinus100@hotmail.com">Ashwin S</a>
46 
 * @author Maarten Coene
47 
 * @author <a href="mailto:levon@lk.otherinbox.com">Levon Karayan</a>
48 
 * @since 2.0
49 
 * @version $Id$
50 
 */
51

252 
    // Generic array
253 
    //-----------------------------------------------------------------------
254 
    /**
255 
     * Create a type-safe generic array.
256 
     *
257 
     * <p>Arrays are covariant i.e. they cannot be created from a generic type:</p>
258 
     *
259 
     * <pre>
260 
    public static &lt;T&gt; T[] createAnArray(int size)
261 
    {
262 
        return T[size]; // compiler error here
263 
    }
264 
    public static &lt;T&gt; T[] createAnArray(int size)
265 
    {
266 
        return (T[])Object[size]; // ClassCastException at runtime
267 
    }
268 
     * </pre>
269 
     *
270 
     * <p>Therefore new arrays of generic types can be created with this method, e.g. an arrays
271 
     * of Strings:</p>
272 
     *
273 
     * <pre>
274 
    String[] array = ArrayUtils.toArray("1", "2");
275 
    String[] emptyArray = ArrayUtils.&lt;String&gt;toArray();
276 
     * </pre>
277 
     *
278 
     * The method is typically used in scenarios, where the caller itself uses generic types
279 
     * that have to be combined into an array.
280 
     *
281 
     * Note, this method makes only sense to provide arguments of the same type so that the
282 
     * compiler can deduce the type of the array itself. While it is possible to select the
283 
     * type explicitly like in <code>Number[] array = ArrayUtils.<Number>toArray(new
284 
     * Integer(42), new Double(Math.PI))</code>, there is no real advantage to <code>new
285 
     * Number[] {new Integer(42), new Double(Math.PI)}</code> anymore.
286 
     *
287 
     * @param  <T>   the array's element type
288 
     * @param  items the items of the array
289 
     * @return the array
290 
     * @since  3.0
291 
     */
292 
    public static <T> T[] toArray(final T... items)
293 
    {
294 2 1. toArray : replaced return value with null for org/apache/commons/lang3/ArrayUtils::toArray → SURVIVED
2. toArray : mutated return of Object value for org/apache/commons/lang3/ArrayUtils::toArray to ( if (x != null) null else throw new RuntimeException ) → KILLED
 
        return items;
295 
    }
